<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How much should I spend on an engagement ring?", answer: "The classic rules are 1, 2, or 3 months of salary, but they're a marketing invention from a 1947 De Beers ad campaign — there's no actual relationship rule about ring spending. Most modern jewelers and financial advisors recommend spending what you can afford comfortably without going into debt. The Knot's 2024 survey found the US average is around $5,500 for an engagement ring. The most common bracket is $1,000–$3,000, used by about 30% of buyers." },
  { question: "Is the 3 month salary rule real?", answer: "It was invented by De Beers in 1947 to sell more diamonds. The original campaign suggested 1 month's salary; in the 1980s De Beers updated it to 2 months; and the 3-month version came later. None of these are based on tradition or finance — they're advertising. Modern jewelers and personal finance experts consistently recommend ignoring the rule and spending only what fits your budget." },
  { question: "How can I get a bigger-looking ring for less?", answer: "Choose lab-grown diamonds (30–50% cheaper than natural for the same size and quality), pick a halo setting (smaller center stone surrounded by smaller diamonds for visual impact), shop online from reputable retailers like Blue Nile or James Allen (saves 20–40% over physical stores), choose a slightly lower color or clarity grade (the eye can't tell the difference), and consider moissanite or a sapphire for the lowest cost while keeping a stunning look." },
  { question: "Should I tell my partner the budget?", answer: "Most experienced jewelers say yes for couples in committed long-term relationships. Modern proposals are increasingly collaborative — the partner often picks the style, the ring shopper sets the budget. If you want to keep the proposal a surprise, ask their close friend or family member to subtly find out preferences without revealing the plan. Don't surprise someone with a ring that goes against their style or values." },
  { question: "What if my partner wants something more expensive than I can afford?", answer: "Have an honest conversation about budget. Suggest going up in size or quality at the next anniversary, or upgrading the setting later. Many couples buy a smaller starter ring and upgrade after 5–10 years when finances are more stable. Some couples skip a diamond entirely in favor of a meaningful family heirloom or a colored gemstone. The ring is a symbol — its meaning isn't tied to its price tag." }
]) %>

